gland","Honeychurch, North Tawton district, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Honeychurch, Devon, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Honeychurch, Devon, Devonshire, England, UK":"Honeychurch, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Bengeworth, Wychavon district, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Bengeworth, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","Honeychurch, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Honeychurch, Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"WEEKES","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Weeks   or   Wicks  . This form of the surname is frequent in Barbados."],"variants":[{"name":"Weeks","meanings":["English: variant of   Wicks  .","Americanized form of Norwegian and Swedish   Vik  .","History: This surname was brought to North America independently by several different bearers in the 17th and 18th centuries. One of the earliest on record is Leonard Weeks, who emigrated from Somerset, England, to Portsmouth, NH, some time before 1656. — William Weeks, recorded in Edgartown, Martha's Vineyard, MA, from 1653 onward, was probably a cousin or other relative of the John Wickes mentioned at   Wickes  ."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Norse, originally a byname meaning ‘bride, wife’; in mythology the name of Thor's golden-haired wife."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":30,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William WEEKES was born in 1425, in Honeychurch, Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, LORD William FitzWilliam de Weeks III, was 22 and his mother, Mary Williamson, was 20. He had at least 1 son with Jane Prideaux. He died on 6 September 1483, in Honeychurch, Devon, England, at the age of 58."},"et":{"1425–Sept 6, 1483":"1425–6. september 1483","1425–1483":"1425–1483","1425–Female":"1425–Surnud","1440–1483":"1440–1483","1403–1480":"1403–1480","1405–1430":"1405–1430","1425":"1425","1403":"1403","Sept 6, 1483":"6. september 1483","1455":"1455","1430":"1430","1440":"1440","1483":"1483","6 September 1483":"6. september 1483","1480":"1480","31 March 1480":"31. märts 1480","1405":"1405","Honeychurch, Devon, England":"Honeychurch, Devon, England","Honeychurch, North Tawton district, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Honeychurch, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Honeychurch, Devon, Devonshire, England, UK":"Honeychurch, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bengeworth, Wychavon district, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Bengeworth, Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Honeychurch, Devon, Engl